                "name": "Sherridan Schwartz",
                "href": "/profile/Sherridan-Schwartz-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "Other Americans ask me about Brazil (one of my areas of specialty) quite a bit. I sometimes think Americans think of Brazil like a good-looking, gregarious popular cousin - works just enough to get along, but relies on his good looks and social skills to get ahead. It's that cousin who is friendly, social always welcomes you over for food drinks, and music - but really doesn't want to discuss politics or heavy issues.  In reality, I know Brazilians to be a hard-working people focused on growing their economy and democracy despite challenges, keeping ahead of technology and environmental issues, making a Herculean effort to educate tens of thousands of their college students abroad and across the world (the Brazilian Scientific Mobility Program a.k.a. Ciencias Sem Fronteiras) and working to change the perceptions of their country by hosting the World Cup, the Olympics and other international events.  ",
